n: Identifying the Jew and Making Sense of Modernity) of how such writers drew upon representations of Jewish corporeality in order to work through their particular situations in Gentile modernity. From Heine's ironic lizards to Kafka's Red Peter and Siodmak's Wolf Man, Bestiarium Judaicum brings together Jewish cultural studies and critical animal studies to ferret out these writers' engagement with the bestial answers upon which the Jewish and animal questions converged and by which varieties of the species "Jew" were identified.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aJews - Identity - History - 19th century. 0aJewsxIdentityxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aAntisemitism-response.  aCultural-studies.  aGerman-Jewish writers.  aHuman-animal-difference.  aIdentification.  aJewish Question.  aQuestion of the Animal.  adiscourse-analysis.  amodernity.  arepresentation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311072900940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823275618zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823275618423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823275618.jpg  a978-3-11-072900-9  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK